Scala Doesn't have any operator
Operators are defined as method in scala.
Every value in Scala is an object
Every method in Scala is an operator
Scala allows object oriented notation(. notation) or operator notation ( without .) for making a method call.

Use of method/Operator with one or more parameters-

One input parameters to operator / method-
------------------
Syntax -  <object> <space> <method/operator> <space> <parameter>
<object> <.> <method/operator>(<parameter>)

scala> val i = 10
i: Int = 10

scala> i.+(20) //Object oriented syntax using '.'
res5: Int = 30

scala> i + 20 //Methemetical Syntax without '.'
res6: Int = 30

scala> i compare 20
res7: Int = -1

scala> i .compare(20)
res8: Int = -1

scala> -5.abs
res11: Int = 5

Multiple input parameters to operator / method-
------------------
Syntax - <object><space><method/operator><space><parameter> //not working yet to check right syntax.

Unary Operator-
-----------------
Operator which operates on only one value.
There are only 4 unary operators in Scala-
+ positive
- Negative
! Logical Not
~ Binary One's complement.
------------------------
